        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>London</placeName>
                <date>Novr. 21St 1854</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">My dear friend.</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Once again am I on the<lb/> move, about to cross the wide
                    <placeName>Atlantic</placeName>, and return to my old feeding<lb/> ground,
                    <placeName>Kingston, Jamaica</placeName>. The departure of <persName>Mr. D. E.
                        Sauson<add>?</add></persName>, <persName>Mrs.<lb/> Nathan's</persName> only
                brother, for the “land of life” on the <date>21st</date> Ulto<add>?</add>
                occasions<lb/> this more, nay, makes it obligatory; for not only are my interests
                at<lb/> stake, but a young widow and three helpless babies and, by will,
                solemnly<lb/> committed to my future care. It is a very onerous charge, but the
                work<lb/> must be done; may the Omnipotent grant me strength to perform it
                faithfully.<lb/> My brother in law was but 31 years of age, his disease scarlet
                fever, and<lb/> after 4 days illness his spirit fled. <persName>Mrs.
                    Nathan</persName> for several weeks prior<lb/> to the receipt of the
                intelligence had been alarmingly ill; and you can<lb/> conceive the shock the news
                imparted to her enfeebled frame. Had this<lb/> melancholy event not occurred, its
                summer had probably seen us again in<lb/>
                <placeName>America</placeName>, its country, par excellence, in my and
                    <persName>Mrs. N's</persName> ideas. But it was<lb/> not to be.
                    <placeName>Jamaica</placeName> will be henceforth my abode, not from choice,
                but<lb/> circumstances. My heart is too full, and my brain too busy to write
                you<lb/> more. I have not recd. Your Bible, nor my <persName>Job</persName>. When
                the latter is<lb/> returned to you send it on to <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>, for
                I value it as the gift of a good<lb/> friend. By forwarding your letters to
                    <persName>Mrs. HS. Henry</persName>
                <placeName>16 Broadway New York</placeName><lb/> they will always reach me. Remember
                us affectionately to <persName>Miss Gratz</persName>,<lb/> &amp;
                    <persName>Ms.Hart</persName> &amp; <persName>Miss Louisa</persName>, the
                    <persName>Florance</persName> family, <persName>Mr. Abraham
                    N<add>?</add></persName> &amp; family, and all<lb/> old friends, and believe
                me</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Your's as of old</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <persName role="author">M. N. Nathan</persName>
            </p>
